body:
$!As an employer, you need to work out and record the correct amount of tax and National Insurance on holiday pay for your employees.$!

##What to report and pay

If you continue to pay an employee as normal while they're on holiday, this isn't a benefit. It just counts as normal earnings. Continue to deduct and pay PAYE tax and Class 1 National Insurance through payroll.

^There are different rules if you provide holiday pay in advance, or run any special holiday pay schemes. See HMRC's [guide to holiday pay and PAYE.](http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/paye/payroll/special-pay/holiday.htm "guide to holiday pay and PAYE"){:rel="external"}

##Technical guidance

The following guides contain more detailed information:

- [holiday pay](http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/manuals/eimanual/eim01470.htm "holiday pay"){:rel="external"}

- [Class 1 National Insurance: holiday pay](http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/manuals/nimmanual/nim02200.htm "Class 1 National Insurance: holiday pay"){:rel="external"}

- [‘Employer further guide to PAYE and NICs’ (CWG2): see chapter 2, sections 38–43](http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/guidance/cwg2.htm "‘Employer further guide to PAYE and NICs’ (CWG2): see chapter 2, sections 38–43"){:rel="external"}

*[HMRC]:HM Revenue & Customs
*[PAYE]:Pay As You Earn
